BRUCELLOSIS, BOVINE - USA (MONTANA)
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 5 Dec 2014
Source: Bozeman Daily Chronicle [edited]
http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/agriculture/brucellosis-found-in-madison-county-herd/article_1591f9fe-7cd5-11e4-b848-9b8786b28f5c.html


A cow in a large Madison County cattle herd has brucellosis, according to the Montana Department of Livestock.

The cow was identified during a herd test by a producer whose cattle graze within the state's Designated Surveillance Area. The National Veterinary Services Laboratories in Ames, Iowa, confirmed the infection.

State veterinarian Marty Zaluski said the area has been quarantined and adjacent livestock producers are being notified.

The state is not at risk of losing its brucellosis-free status based on regulations from the U.S. Department of Agriculture Animal & Plant Health Inspection Service.

As with previous cases of brucellosis in livestock, adjacent producers will test livestock as part of an epidemiological investigation to determine the source of the infection. Previous epidemiological investigations of brucellosis in livestock in Montana, Idaho and Wyoming indicated that elk were the most likely source.

"We don't like finding brucellosis-positive cows, but if it's out there, we want to find it before cattle are shipped to market or out of state," Zaluski said. "That's why we have a program; we have to assure other states we're doing everything we can to manage this endemic wildlife disease problem."

Similar to affected herds in the past, the low infection rate indicates early detection. "It demonstrates that our aggressive surveillance program finds the disease before it is allowed to spread within the herd, which reduces costs for producers and minimizes risk for our trading partners," he said.

The state has now found at least one case of brucellosis in cattle in 5 of the past 8 years.

